excerpt: Shops, restaurants & night clubs surround this bay with coral reefs, a popular resort destination.
detail_description: Naama Bay is a vibrant resort destination surrounded by shops, restaurants, and nightclubs. The bay boasts stunning coral reefs, making it a popular spot for snorkeling and diving enthusiasts. Visitors can explore the bustling Old Market, enjoy the lively atmosphere of SOHO Square, and indulge in shopping at Sharm el Sheikh Port. Additionally, Naama Bay offers a variety of dining options including traditional British meals at The Tavern Bar and Roof as well as Indian and Italian cuisine at The Camel Bar & Roof.
name: Naama Bay
address: Egypt

excerpt: Modernized Old Town souk around Al-Sahaba Mosque, known for spices, perfumes, clothes & street food.
detail_description: The Old Market in Sharm el Sheikh, also known as Sharm al-Maya, is a vibrant and modernized souk located around the Al-Sahaba Mosque. This bustling area is filled with traditional Arabic lanterns, shisha pipes, and intricately carved woodwork. Visitors can explore a variety of shops offering spices, perfumes, clothing, and authentic street food. The market comes alive in the evening with lively restaurants and cafes where visitors can immerse themselves in the local culture.
name: Old Market Sharm el Sheikh
address: Entrance El-Souk, Sharm El Sheikh 2, South Sinai Governorate 8761130, Egypt

detail_description: Located near the Old Market in Sharm el Sheikh, Al Mustafa Mosque is a stunning example of Hispano-Moorish architecture. Completed in 2008, it replicates the iconic Al-Azhar Mosque in Cairo and is particularly beautiful when illuminated at night. The mosque is surrounded by gardens leading to the Red Sea beach, creating a relaxing atmosphere for visitors.
name: Mustafa Mosque
address: V7RX+XVJ, حي النور, Sharm El Sheikh 2, South Sinai Governorate 8761251, Egypt

excerpt: Sharm El Sheikh, alternatively rendered Sharm el-Sheikh, Sharm el Sheikh, or Sharm El-Sheikh, is an Egyptian city on the southern tip of the Sinai Peninsula, in South Sinai Governorate, on the coastal strip along the Red Sea. Its population is approximately 13,000 as of 2023. Wikipedia.
detail_description: Sharm El-Sheikh is a popular resort town in Egypt, located between the Sinai Peninsula's desert and the Red Sea. It's renowned for its beautiful sandy beaches, crystal-clear waters, and vibrant coral reefs. Naama Bay offers a lively atmosphere with its palm tree-lined promenade filled with various bars and restaurants. The Ras Muhammad National Park is a top diving spot, boasting diverse marine life around the Shark and Yolanda reefs as well as the Thistlegorm wreck.
name: Sharm El-Sheikh
address: Sharm El Sheikh 2, South Sinai Governorate, Egypt

excerpt: Vibrant square featuring fountains, restaurants & lounges, plus an ice rink & other entertainment.
detail_description: SOHO Square Sharm El Sheikh is a vibrant and popular tourist attraction located in Sharks Bay, just a short distance from Naama Bay and Nabq. The square features an array of entertainment options including fountains, restaurants, lounges, and an ice rink. Visitors can enjoy the mesmerizing dancing fountain show with Egyptian music and songs, creating a cheerful atmosphere for all guests. Additionally, the square boasts advanced lighting systems that add to its artistic charm.
name: SOHO Square Sharm El Sheikh
address: SOHO Square, South Sinai Governorate 46628, Egypt

This mosque, reminiscent of tales from One Thousand and One Nights, welcomes visitors but has a dress code for women. While the city is renowned for its beaches, it also boasts cultural and historical sites like Al Sahaba Mosque. Built by the Egyptian Army, this mosque showcases impressive architecture and design details both inside and out.
name: Al-Sahaba Mosque
address: V78W+H39, Sharm El Sheikh 1, South Sinai Governorate 8761131, Egypt

detail_description: Abo Ali restaurant in the old market is a charming spot to unwind and enjoy a delightful meal.

excerpt: Contemporary Coptic place of worship with rectangular towers & frescoes & murals of biblical scenes.
detail_description: The Heavenly Cathedral is a contemporary Coptic place of worship located near the Old Market in Sharm El-Sheikh. This landmark, built in 2010, features innovative stained glass windows and creative drawings on its ceilings and walls depicting biblical scenes. It is highly revered among Coptic visitors and is considered one of the 10 most beautiful churches in the world.
name: The Heavenly Cathedral
address: V7QW+65F, Al Maahad Al Dini, Sharm El Sheikh 2, South Sinai Governorate 8761225, Egypt

detail_description: The King Tut Museum, located in Genena City, is a top attraction in Sharm El Sheikh. It features replicas of King Tut's collection from the Egyptian Museum, all executed under the supervision of the State Ministry of Antiquities. With 135 diverse pieces and photographs documenting the tomb's opening, visitors can explore over 2000 square meters of art and history to gain an understanding of ancient Egyptian culture.
name: King Tut Museum
address: W85C+94G, خليج نعمة, Sharm El Sheikh 1, South Sinai Governorate 8763011, Egypt

detail_description: Sharm El Sheikh International Airport is the quickest way to kickstart your Sharm El Sheikh adventure, conveniently located just an hour away from Cairo. The airport consists of two passenger terminals - one for domestic flights and the other for international arrivals. Despite its compact size, it boasts three spacious halls to accommodate a large influx of global travelers seeking unforgettable Sharm El Sheikh tours. The airport's efficient design has made it a significant landmark in Sinai over the past 30 years.
name: Sharm El Sheikh International Airport
address: 2 El-Salam, Sharm El Sheikh 2, South Sinai Governorate 8752202, Egypt
